WEBVTT

00:00:07.020 --> 00:00:07.390
PROFESSOR: Hi.

00:00:07.390 --> 00:00:08.870
Welcome back to recitation.

00:00:08.870 --> 00:00:11.580
We've been talking about
applications of integration,

00:00:11.580 --> 00:00:14.080
including finding the areas
between curves.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:16.530
So I have here a nice little
region that I like.

00:00:16.530 --> 00:00:17.670
I think it's kind of cute.

00:00:17.670 --> 00:00:21.990
So it's the region between
y equals sine x and y

00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:23.720
equals cosine x.

00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:26.270
And, you know, those two curves
cross each other over

00:00:26.270 --> 00:00:26.850
and over again.

00:00:26.850 --> 00:00:27.836
They wrap around each other.

00:00:27.836 --> 00:00:31.540
So I'm just interested in the
region between the two

00:00:31.540 --> 00:00:32.980
consecutive points
where they cross.

00:00:32.980 --> 00:00:37.500
So here, you know, so at pi over
4 we have sine x equals--

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:39.790
sine pi over 4 equals
cosine pi over 4.

00:00:39.790 --> 00:00:43.160
And at 5 pi over 4 they're also
equal again, down in the

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:45.030
third quadrant there.

00:00:45.030 --> 00:00:51.360
So, the question is to compute
the area of this region that

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:53.400
they bound between
those two points.

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:56.300
So why don't you take a couple
of minutes, work through that,

00:00:56.300 --> 00:00:57.810
come back and we can work
through it together.

00:01:05.970 --> 00:01:07.130
All right, welcome back.

00:01:07.130 --> 00:01:11.480
So, from this picture it's
pretty easy to see what the

00:01:11.480 --> 00:01:13.130
region of integration is.

00:01:13.130 --> 00:01:15.380
I mean what the bounds
on x will be.

00:01:15.380 --> 00:01:19.390
As we said, x has to go the
left, I mean, you could--

00:01:19.390 --> 00:01:20.640
sorry, let me start over.

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:23.100
You could do any two consecutive
intersection

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:23.710
points you want, right?

00:01:23.710 --> 00:01:26.480
The area is the same in any case
because of the symmetry

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:26.953
of these two functions.

00:01:26.953 --> 00:01:27.850
So, OK.

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:31.340
But the first two that are
easiest for me to find are

00:01:31.340 --> 00:01:33.460
this pi over 4 and
this 5 pi over 4.

00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:34.650
So I'm going to do those two.

00:01:34.650 --> 00:01:37.700
If you wanted, you could have
done it with a different pair

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:39.580
of consecutive points.

00:01:39.580 --> 00:01:42.490
But, once we've agreed that sort
of these first two are

00:01:42.490 --> 00:01:44.330
the ones I'm going to
do, then it's easy.

00:01:44.330 --> 00:01:46.730
I know that they're pi over
4 and 5 pi over 4.

00:01:46.730 --> 00:01:48.990
So that's the interval over
which I'm going to be

00:01:48.990 --> 00:01:49.800
integrating.

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:54.020
And then, what I want to do is
just view this region as cut

00:01:54.020 --> 00:01:56.220
into a lot of little
rectangles.

00:01:56.220 --> 00:02:00.810
And I want to integrate the
height of those rectangles in

00:02:00.810 --> 00:02:03.610
order to get the area
of the whole region.

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:06.780
So in this case, the upper curve
is y equals sine x and

00:02:06.780 --> 00:02:09.560
the lower curve is y
equals cosine of x.

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:11.490
So the height of a little--

00:02:11.490 --> 00:02:13.470
you know if I drawn in a
little rectangle here--

00:02:16.470 --> 00:02:18.950
the height of that rectangle
is going to be sine x

00:02:18.950 --> 00:02:20.200
minus cosine x.

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:21.540
Its width is dx.

00:02:21.540 --> 00:02:23.350
And then I add them all
up by integrating.

00:02:23.350 --> 00:02:34.040
So the area is just the integral
from pi over 4 to 5

00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:42.590
pi over 4 of sine x
minus cosine x dx.

00:02:42.590 --> 00:02:44.470
Top minus bottom to
get the height.

00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:46.940
If you did it backwards; if you
wrote cosine minus sine,

00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:50.040
what you would get is exactly
the negative of the area.

00:02:50.040 --> 00:02:53.720
So it's, all right, from pi
over 4 to 5, pi over 4.

00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:55.890
So now, we just have
to integrate this.

00:02:55.890 --> 00:02:58.900
So integral of sine, the
function whose derivative is

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:03.050
sine is minus cosine x.

00:03:03.050 --> 00:03:06.030
And the function whose
derivative is cosine is sine.

00:03:06.030 --> 00:03:17.630
So it's minus sine x between
pi over 4, 5 pi over 4.

00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:20.030
And OK, so now, we just have
to plug in the values.

00:03:20.030 --> 00:03:30.250
So this is equal to minus cosine
5 pi over 4 minus sine

00:03:30.250 --> 00:03:41.027
5 pi over 4 minus minus
cosine pi over 4 minus

00:03:41.027 --> 00:03:43.910
sine pi over 4.

00:03:43.910 --> 00:03:46.450
And I'm sure you can work out
for yourself that this is

00:03:46.450 --> 00:03:54.890
equal to 2 times the square root
of 2 if I haven't botched

00:03:54.890 --> 00:03:56.790
anything terribly.

00:03:56.790 --> 00:03:59.110
So I'll end there.